WEBVTT

00:07.187 --> 00:09.488
‐ Do you know anything
about night swimming?

00:09.488 --> 00:11.824
‐ Well, we do have our share
of tree huggers out here.

00:11.824 --> 00:13.426
‐ Last night,
somebody broke into the house

00:13.460 --> 00:14.563
where I'm staying.

00:14.596 --> 00:16.165
‐ Did you see them?

00:16.199 --> 00:18.671
‐ No, I wasn't there, but
they looked through my stuff.

00:18.704 --> 00:20.675
‐ This brings up a lot for me.

00:20.708 --> 00:23.346
An intruder in the house?
A lot.

00:23.380 --> 00:25.350
‐ I can't walk away
from this.

00:25.384 --> 00:28.691
‐ I don't think that I can
keep going on like this.

00:28.724 --> 00:31.697
[soft dramatic music]

00:31.730 --> 00:34.503
‐ Where was that?
‐ In your jacket pocket.

00:34.536 --> 00:36.272
‐ Percy worked on Don's crew.

00:36.306 --> 00:38.778
‐ Well, they used to go up
together a lot on their own.

00:38.811 --> 00:40.447
‐ What is this shit?
You're telling me

00:40.480 --> 00:43.320
someone didn't poison
her mind with that shit?

00:43.353 --> 00:48.263
‐ That wasn't Percy.
Somebody had control over her.

00:48.296 --> 00:51.837
‐ The ancient lunar goddess
is represented

00:51.870 --> 00:55.143
by the ouroboros...

00:55.177 --> 00:59.151
a snake swallowing
its own tail.

00:59.185 --> 01:04.428
♪ ♪

01:07.502 --> 01:10.474
[dramatic music]

01:10.508 --> 01:17.454
♪ ♪

01:24.736 --> 01:27.207
[waves crashing]

01:27.241 --> 01:30.380
[dramatic music]

01:30.414 --> 01:37.328
♪ ♪

01:42.137 --> 01:43.106
[camera clicks]

01:43.139 --> 01:50.253
♪ ♪

02:06.520 --> 02:08.724
‐ Meg?

02:08.758 --> 02:11.930
‐ You didn't see this,
unless you want one.

02:11.964 --> 02:14.201
‐ No, I don't smoke.

02:14.235 --> 02:18.611
‐ Well, neither do I.
I quit 30 years ago.

02:18.644 --> 02:20.882
I leave Sean
in charge for a week.

02:20.915 --> 02:23.286
Turns everything to shit.

02:23.320 --> 02:25.558
‐ Your boys,
it doesn't bother them,

02:25.591 --> 02:27.294
me being around here?

02:29.198 --> 02:30.802
‐ I don't care what they think.

02:30.835 --> 02:33.574
Please tell me
you found something.

02:33.607 --> 02:34.943
‐ Yeah.

02:34.976 --> 02:38.249
Now, this family crest,

02:38.283 --> 02:39.753
that's, like,
from a boat, right?

02:39.786 --> 02:41.289
You know whose it was?

02:41.322 --> 02:42.792
‐ I don't know it,
but they do have

02:42.826 --> 02:46.767
retired boat logs down
at the harbor master's office.

02:46.800 --> 02:48.269
‐ Okay, great. Thanks.

02:48.303 --> 02:49.773
‐ Where'd you find it?

02:49.806 --> 02:52.244
‐ Oh, I just‐‐
I've been curious

02:52.277 --> 02:53.647
about these
off in the woods areas

02:53.681 --> 02:56.219
that have these ritualized
arrangements and things,

02:56.252 --> 02:57.822
and it was
around one of those.

02:57.856 --> 03:00.795
‐ Yeah, we get those new age
hippie types up here.

03:00.828 --> 03:02.665
‐ [chuckles]

03:02.699 --> 03:06.840
‐ You think this has something
to do with Percy?

03:06.874 --> 03:09.613
‐ Can't tell.

03:09.646 --> 03:12.251
I'm gonna track
this boat thing down.

03:12.284 --> 03:13.587
It's probably nothing.

03:13.621 --> 03:16.459
‐ I'll come with you.

03:16.492 --> 03:19.298
‐ I don't think you need to.

03:19.331 --> 03:22.939
‐ I know everybody
at the office.

03:22.972 --> 03:27.481
♪ ♪

03:27.515 --> 03:30.487
‐ My unloading time
is at 2:00 every day.

03:30.521 --> 03:32.726
And that Brandon Keyser
is always blocking me.

03:32.759 --> 03:34.863
‐ We've been here before.
You can file a report online.

03:34.896 --> 03:37.569
‐ I filed three.
Nothing happens.

03:37.602 --> 03:40.608
‐ They're backlogs.
They'll get to it.

03:40.641 --> 03:43.581
‐ Yeah, right.

03:43.614 --> 03:45.250
‐ Hey, Mike.

03:48.456 --> 03:49.626
‐ Hi, Mrs. Muldoon.

03:49.659 --> 03:51.462
‐ Hi, Patrick.
How you doing?

03:51.496 --> 03:52.999
‐ Good, good.
‐ Good.

03:53.032 --> 03:54.435
We have a question.

03:54.468 --> 03:57.374
We're trying to find
the boat this is from.

03:57.408 --> 03:59.646
Does it match anything
in your records?

03:59.679 --> 04:02.451
‐ We log boats by registration
numbers, not insignia.

04:02.484 --> 04:04.890
‐ Right, but you might
recognize it from somewhere.

04:04.923 --> 04:06.693
‐ Uh‐‐[chuckles]

04:06.727 --> 04:09.432
‐ To me, it reminds me
of the Henderson boat.

04:09.465 --> 04:10.902
The one Dick used to captain.

04:10.935 --> 04:12.438
‐ Yeah, yeah.
But that's not quite it.

04:12.471 --> 04:14.676
[suspenseful music]

04:14.709 --> 04:17.281
‐ Hey, the other harbor master
who's usually here,

04:17.314 --> 04:18.951
what's her name again?

04:18.984 --> 04:21.657
‐ Em Castillo?
She's off today.

04:21.690 --> 04:23.727
I could dig through some files,
see what I come up with.

04:23.761 --> 04:25.363
‐ Yeah, that'd be great.

04:25.397 --> 04:29.472
♪ ♪

04:29.506 --> 04:31.476
‐ She's weird about people
touching her stuff.

04:31.510 --> 04:34.482
‐ No problem, no problem, mate.
Thanks for looking into this.

04:34.516 --> 04:36.587
Meg, we'll be in touch.

04:38.924 --> 04:40.360
‐ Oh, all right.

04:40.393 --> 04:47.474
♪ ♪

05:46.860 --> 05:49.398
[suspenseful music fades]

05:52.805 --> 05:55.745
[soft intriguing music]

05:55.778 --> 06:02.692
♪ ♪

07:08.524 --> 07:11.596
[tense notes]

07:37.080 --> 07:39.118
[objects clacking]

07:39.151 --> 07:42.792
[suspenseful music]

07:42.825 --> 07:49.706
♪ ♪

08:06.172 --> 08:07.909
‐ Is that for me?

08:07.942 --> 08:10.146
‐ Was it you that broke
into the house the other day?

08:10.180 --> 08:11.248
‐ No.

08:12.819 --> 08:14.823
Guess you're making enemies
around here.

08:20.166 --> 08:22.137
These weren't yours to take.

08:22.170 --> 08:24.509
‐ Well, they're evidence now.

08:24.542 --> 08:27.882
‐ Of what?
‐ They were out on the cliffs.

08:29.953 --> 08:31.890
‐ Percy had these with her
when she jumped?

08:31.923 --> 08:36.700
‐ They were set out
by her or someone else.

08:38.937 --> 08:40.641
Maybe it was you?

08:40.674 --> 08:42.144
‐ Is that why you're
investigating me?

08:42.177 --> 08:43.814
‐ Your relationship to Percy.

08:45.718 --> 08:47.020
Why are you hiding it?

08:47.054 --> 08:48.991
‐ I'm not hiding anything.

08:49.024 --> 08:51.062
‐ Well, then,

08:51.095 --> 08:53.199
maybe you could tell me
what you're doing here?

08:53.232 --> 08:54.602
‐ I thought we were
playing a game

08:54.636 --> 08:57.174
where we break into
each other's houses,

08:57.207 --> 08:58.711
see what we can find.

09:01.082 --> 09:03.654
‐ I see.

09:03.687 --> 09:08.764
Your hut by the water,
I found it.

09:08.797 --> 09:11.803
‐ And?

09:11.837 --> 09:15.043
‐ I saw your notes on Percy.

09:17.247 --> 09:21.288
What was that?
Some kind of conversion?

09:23.059 --> 09:23.961
‐ I'd call it growth.

09:23.994 --> 09:26.800
‐ At the hut,
I found blood on the rocks.

09:30.808 --> 09:32.344
‐ I'm not the person
you're looking for.

09:32.377 --> 09:35.216
♪ ♪

09:35.250 --> 09:39.993
And if you come by my house
again, I'm gonna shoot first.

09:40.026 --> 09:42.632
♪ ♪

09:42.665 --> 09:43.867
‐ About that blood,

09:43.901 --> 09:46.606
Chief Raskin is gonna
run forensics on it

09:46.640 --> 09:47.942
and see if
it's a match for Percy.

09:47.975 --> 09:50.113
It's gonna take four
or five days.

09:50.146 --> 09:53.252
But somehow, this case leaks,

09:53.286 --> 09:55.958
and people are gonna
find out sooner.

09:55.991 --> 09:58.664
‐ Are you threatening me?
‐ No.

09:58.697 --> 10:02.337
I'm just being honest with you.

10:02.370 --> 10:06.011
Look, you're an outsider here.
Same as me.

10:06.045 --> 10:08.684
And any sign
that you might have hurt her,

10:08.717 --> 10:11.222
people are gonna assume
the worst about you.

10:11.255 --> 10:13.192
‐ Just like you are.

10:13.226 --> 10:16.933
♪ ♪

10:16.967 --> 10:20.975
‐ Well, maybe.

10:21.008 --> 10:25.818
This is your chance
to set me straight.

10:35.671 --> 10:37.174
[soft dramatic music] ♪ ♪

10:37.207 --> 10:41.382
‐ I always saw her from afar
down by the dock.

10:41.415 --> 10:44.021
♪ ♪

10:44.054 --> 10:48.396
She was 25
and loving being in charge.

10:48.429 --> 10:50.400
At least that's how I saw her.

10:50.433 --> 10:53.272
‐ And then something
in her changed,

10:53.306 --> 10:56.780
like, around two years ago?

10:58.115 --> 10:59.084
‐ Yeah.

11:01.756 --> 11:04.394
It's like she became
a totally different person.

11:06.065 --> 11:10.006
Started drinking.
Drugs too, probably.

11:10.039 --> 11:11.877
♪ ♪

11:11.910 --> 11:14.014
She became
completely withdrawn.

11:14.047 --> 11:15.416
♪ ♪

11:15.450 --> 11:17.320
And then she was gone.

11:17.354 --> 11:20.026
♪ ♪

11:20.059 --> 11:21.796
She left the island.

11:21.830 --> 11:25.470
Probably a few months went by.

11:25.504 --> 11:29.044
And when she got back,
she was worse.

11:29.077 --> 11:32.050
It's like she was a shell
of who she'd been before.

11:32.083 --> 11:34.187
♪ ♪

11:34.221 --> 11:38.029
‐ That's where you'd see her,
by that dock?

11:38.530 --> 11:41.068
‐ Yeah.
I was working nights,

11:41.101 --> 11:44.441
so I'd always
see her there alone.

11:44.474 --> 11:46.378
‐ Why that spot, do you think?

11:46.412 --> 11:49.451
‐ Something happened
to her down there?

11:49.484 --> 11:51.021
I don't know what.

11:51.055 --> 11:52.792
‐ At some point,
you started to talk to her

11:52.825 --> 11:55.196
and thinking
you could help her, right?

11:55.230 --> 11:57.500
‐ She's the one who started it.

11:57.535 --> 12:00.507
[insects chirping]

12:00.541 --> 12:03.479
[suspenseful music]

12:03.513 --> 12:08.289
♪ ♪

12:08.322 --> 12:09.458
‐ Hey.

12:09.491 --> 12:12.230
♪ ♪

12:12.264 --> 12:13.767
What are you doing?

12:13.800 --> 12:16.806
♪ ♪

12:16.840 --> 12:21.081
‐ Nothing.
Just, uh, taking a moment.

12:21.115 --> 12:23.085
‐ What's that in your hand?

12:23.119 --> 12:26.960
♪ ♪

12:26.993 --> 12:29.364
It's embarrassing
I don't know this

12:29.398 --> 12:31.235
after seeing you around
all these years,

12:31.268 --> 12:32.437
but where are you from?

12:32.470 --> 12:34.976
‐ Baltimore.

12:35.009 --> 12:36.045
‐ Why'd you leave?

12:36.078 --> 12:39.986
‐ I needed to do my own thing
away from my family.

12:40.019 --> 12:45.496
‐ Yeah, I tried that.
Didn't work out so well.

12:45.531 --> 12:47.535
What are they like?

12:47.568 --> 12:51.509
‐ My family?
Uh, like most.

12:51.543 --> 12:52.979
You know, they try.

12:53.012 --> 12:56.118
But they damage
even when they don't mean to.

12:56.151 --> 12:57.989
‐ Damage how?

12:59.592 --> 13:01.428
‐ You know, they're so
caught up in their own pain,

13:01.462 --> 13:04.034
they end up hurting
everyone around them.

13:07.040 --> 13:08.877
‐ Maybe they don't know
another way.

13:08.910 --> 13:11.415
‐ That's the whole point
though, isn't it?

13:11.448 --> 13:14.321
You gotta try.

13:14.354 --> 13:15.858
My aunt was different.

13:15.891 --> 13:20.834
She, uh, introduced me
to just other ways of being.

13:20.868 --> 13:22.437
‐ Is that what you do here?

13:24.575 --> 13:26.880
Is it like Wiccan or something?

13:28.182 --> 13:31.856
‐ [chuckles]
‐ Sorry.

13:31.890 --> 13:33.159
I don't know anything.

13:33.192 --> 13:38.302
I just‐‐I've seen some things
around the island.

13:38.336 --> 13:40.974
Women doing things.

13:41.008 --> 13:44.047
It's only women, isn't it?

13:44.081 --> 13:47.621
‐ I just pull from things
that inspire me.

13:47.655 --> 13:50.026
It's mostly just
about embracing nature.

13:50.059 --> 13:52.497
But not a lot of people
are open to it

13:52.531 --> 13:56.305
because it means
accepting destruction.

13:56.338 --> 13:58.409
[ominous music]

13:58.442 --> 14:00.914
‐ Destruction?

14:00.948 --> 14:03.052
‐ Yeah.
It's nature's cycle.

14:03.085 --> 14:06.058
Without death,
there's no rebirth.

14:06.091 --> 14:08.329
We just try to tap into that.

14:08.362 --> 14:10.500
♪ ♪

14:10.534 --> 14:12.505
‐ But why?

14:12.538 --> 14:15.611
‐ To feel whole.

14:15.644 --> 14:18.349
To understand our place
in all this.

14:18.382 --> 14:22.457
♪ ♪

14:22.490 --> 14:25.196
‐ Can you teach me?

14:25.229 --> 14:30.173
‐ I don't‐‐you know,
it's not really about teaching.

14:30.206 --> 14:31.475
♪ ♪

14:31.509 --> 14:35.951
‐ Just tell me how to start.

14:35.984 --> 14:38.389
‐ Well...

14:38.422 --> 14:40.627
you gotta respect the ocean.

14:40.661 --> 14:42.998
Can't overfish.

14:43.032 --> 14:45.537
‐ Like me and my family?
‐ Yeah.

14:45.571 --> 14:47.541
‐ [chuckles]

14:47.575 --> 14:54.555
♪ ♪

14:54.589 --> 14:57.293
‐ I wanna learn.

14:57.327 --> 14:59.632
Please.

14:59.665 --> 15:03.105
I really need
something like this.

15:03.139 --> 15:05.243
‐ Why?

15:05.276 --> 15:09.351
♪ ♪

15:09.384 --> 15:12.658
‐ I haven't slept in two years.
[chuckles uncomfortably]

15:12.691 --> 15:16.533
♪ ♪

15:16.566 --> 15:20.006
[soft dramatic music]

15:20.039 --> 15:22.277
‐ Point to the first thing
that you notice,

15:22.310 --> 15:23.680
that you're drawn to.

15:23.713 --> 15:25.584
[birds singing]

15:25.617 --> 15:27.153
Don't think.

15:30.393 --> 15:31.963
‐ Is that wrong?

15:52.470 --> 15:54.241
‐ What do you feel?

15:54.274 --> 15:57.581
‐ I don't know.
A dead tree?

15:57.615 --> 15:59.184
‐ Try to feel its pulse.

16:00.621 --> 16:02.123
It's like listening.

16:12.443 --> 16:13.713
‐ I don't get this.

16:13.747 --> 16:15.316
‐ Just stay with it.

16:22.230 --> 16:24.434
‐ I feel stupid.
It's a dead tree.

16:24.467 --> 16:26.271
‐ It's a reflection of you.

16:28.409 --> 16:30.179
You chose it.

16:31.114 --> 16:32.350
‐ Are you fucking with me?
Is this a joke?

16:32.383 --> 16:34.020
‐ What?
No.

16:34.054 --> 16:35.223
‐ I can't do this.

16:35.256 --> 16:37.360
‐ Hey.

16:37.393 --> 16:40.166
Just...sit.

16:43.239 --> 16:44.341
Just sit.

16:53.660 --> 16:57.367
Imagine that the ocean...

16:57.400 --> 16:59.772
the trees...

16:59.805 --> 17:03.780
the birds you hear right now...

17:03.813 --> 17:08.222
everything around you
is reaching out to you...

17:08.255 --> 17:10.794
and touching you
with this hand.

17:10.827 --> 17:15.637
‐ [inhales deeply]

17:15.671 --> 17:17.508
[exhales deeply]

17:17.541 --> 17:20.514
‐ This is love.

17:20.547 --> 17:24.755
♪ ♪

17:24.789 --> 17:27.393
Your whole life,
you've been looking for it.

17:27.427 --> 17:31.502
And it's been
right here all along.

17:31.536 --> 17:36.478
You don't have to do anything
to prove yourself.

17:36.512 --> 17:38.683
You don't have to be
anything you're not.

17:38.717 --> 17:41.823
♪ ♪

17:41.856 --> 17:45.496
You already belong.

17:45.530 --> 17:47.701
You always have.

17:47.735 --> 17:54.815
♪ ♪

18:42.544 --> 18:45.349
‐ We worked together
for a couple months.

18:50.259 --> 18:51.663
‐ You were friends?

18:51.696 --> 18:55.269
‐ No.
Not exactly.

18:57.240 --> 18:59.745
There was something in her
that she wanted to exorcise,

18:59.779 --> 19:01.749
and she wanted my help.

19:01.783 --> 19:04.154
‐ Right.
Yeah, what was it?

19:04.187 --> 19:06.224
"Free the bone from the flesh."

19:08.663 --> 19:10.499
Those your words?

19:10.534 --> 19:11.903
‐ Yeah.

19:13.272 --> 19:14.909
She latched onto that.

19:17.413 --> 19:21.355
‐ And all these things
were used in your sessions?

19:21.388 --> 19:24.595
[ominous music]

19:24.628 --> 19:26.331
♪ ♪

19:26.365 --> 19:28.636
‐ I can't talk about those.

19:28.670 --> 19:31.776
♪ ♪

19:31.809 --> 19:34.247
They're personal to Percy.

19:34.280 --> 19:36.753
‐ Yeah. But she isn't here
to talk about it,

19:36.786 --> 19:38.489
but maybe she'd want to.

19:38.523 --> 19:41.829
I don't understand.
Why are you holding back now?

19:41.863 --> 19:44.267
‐ You wouldn't understand
even if I told you.

19:44.300 --> 19:46.873
‐ Maybe I wouldn't at first...

19:46.906 --> 19:48.943
♪ ♪

19:48.977 --> 19:51.816
But I'll try.

19:51.849 --> 19:55.690
♪ ♪

19:55.724 --> 19:56.959
‐ I can't.

19:56.993 --> 19:59.565
‐ Hey, look, I understand.

19:59.598 --> 20:02.638
This is a risk for you,
going back.

20:02.671 --> 20:05.342
You tried to bring something
out of Percy, right?

20:05.376 --> 20:10.286
Something that she was
so afraid of, right?

20:10.319 --> 20:13.425
You were so close,
but that thing,

20:13.459 --> 20:14.929
whatever it was,

20:14.962 --> 20:17.568
it's what I've been
trying to figure out.

20:17.601 --> 20:20.841
♪ ♪

20:20.874 --> 20:24.582
‐ The only way
I can trust you...

20:24.615 --> 20:26.586
is if you do
the things she did.

20:26.619 --> 20:28.790
♪ ♪

20:28.823 --> 20:32.831
It's the only way
you'll understand.

20:32.865 --> 20:35.302
‐ I'll do it.

20:35.336 --> 20:38.242
‐ It means we'll have
to humble ourselves.

20:38.275 --> 20:39.444
It'll be painful.

20:39.477 --> 20:42.718
♪ ♪

20:42.751 --> 20:46.458
‐ It's okay.
I'm ready.

20:46.491 --> 20:48.362
♪ ♪

20:48.395 --> 20:49.565
‐ Now?

20:50.767 --> 20:52.270
‐ Now.

21:02.758 --> 21:07.968
[dramatic music] ♪ ♪

21:08.001 --> 21:10.907
‐ The water's only 42 degrees.

21:10.941 --> 21:13.245
It's gonna feel like
you can't breathe.

21:14.548 --> 21:16.017
Don't fight it.

21:20.059 --> 21:22.396
You have to
fully submerge yourself.

21:26.806 --> 21:30.547
A lot of people give up at
this point because of the cold.

21:30.580 --> 21:31.749
You don't have to keep going.

21:31.782 --> 21:38.897
♪ ♪

21:44.073 --> 21:45.176
‐ [gasping]

21:45.209 --> 21:48.917
‐ That area that's so tight
right here,

21:48.950 --> 21:50.352
that's our pride.

21:52.558 --> 21:54.728
We let our ego control us.

21:56.464 --> 21:57.935
You're not ready.

22:05.617 --> 22:12.664
♪ ♪

22:12.698 --> 22:14.635
You're still not ready.

22:14.668 --> 22:18.075
♪ ♪

22:18.108 --> 22:20.580
‐ [sighs]

22:20.614 --> 22:21.983
You enjoy this?

22:22.016 --> 22:24.688
‐ Honestly?
No.

22:24.722 --> 22:29.865
♪ ♪

22:29.899 --> 22:31.869
Let go of what
you think should happen.

22:31.903 --> 22:35.777
‐ [breathes slowly]

22:35.810 --> 22:38.750
[slow dramatic music]

22:38.783 --> 22:41.856
♪ ♪

22:41.889 --> 22:43.726
‐ Just wait.

22:43.760 --> 22:47.133
♪ ♪

22:47.166 --> 22:48.135
Now.

22:48.168 --> 22:52.578
♪ ♪

22:52.611 --> 22:54.615
‐ [groans]

22:54.648 --> 22:56.852
♪ ♪

22:56.886 --> 22:58.388
‐ Stay with it.

22:59.925 --> 23:04.467
Keep going.
‐ [breathes heavily]

23:04.500 --> 23:07.774
‐ Keep going.
Let it through.

23:07.808 --> 23:10.513
‐ [groaning]

23:10.547 --> 23:16.157
♪ ♪

23:16.191 --> 23:17.995
Ah!

23:25.944 --> 23:29.017
[fire crackling]

23:29.050 --> 23:30.486
‐ After two months
of working together,

23:30.520 --> 23:32.490
she was still blocked,

23:32.524 --> 23:36.031
so I had had her
pick five objects.

23:36.064 --> 23:38.803
Each one would represent
a relationship

23:38.836 --> 23:40.472
that was holding her back.

23:41.976 --> 23:44.915
‐ These are people in her life?

23:44.949 --> 23:47.019
‐ So she could release them.

23:48.990 --> 23:51.929
[soft dramatic music]

23:51.963 --> 23:56.171
♪ ♪

23:56.204 --> 23:57.908
‐ This one CJ's.

23:57.941 --> 24:01.047
♪ ♪

24:01.081 --> 24:06.525
That first night
I went to apologize...

24:06.559 --> 24:09.798
but I just made
everything worse for him.

24:09.832 --> 24:15.677
♪ ♪

24:15.710 --> 24:17.547
[door opens]

24:17.581 --> 24:18.850
♪ ♪

24:18.883 --> 24:20.820
[tense music]

24:20.854 --> 24:23.526
‐ You slept here?
‐ I'm sorry.

24:23.559 --> 24:25.029
♪ ♪

24:25.062 --> 24:26.632
‐ Who do you think you are?

24:26.666 --> 24:28.670
‐ What are you doing
in my room? Get out!

24:28.703 --> 24:30.674
‐ [speaking Cantonese]

24:30.707 --> 24:32.644
‐ Percy, don't leave.

24:32.678 --> 24:34.648
‐ I didn't mean to.
I'm so sorry.

24:34.682 --> 24:38.823
‐ You don't go near him
ever again.

24:38.856 --> 24:40.894
You hear me?

24:40.927 --> 24:43.131
‐ Percy?

24:43.165 --> 24:44.768
What the hell's
wrong with you?

24:44.802 --> 24:47.607
‐ [speaking Cantonese]

24:49.177 --> 24:51.247
[speaking Cantonese]

24:51.281 --> 24:54.621
‐ I feel sick thinking
about it.

24:54.655 --> 24:56.692
♪ ♪

24:56.726 --> 24:58.261
‐ Keep going.

24:58.295 --> 25:05.510
♪ ♪

25:09.283 --> 25:12.023
‐ I knew leaving Clark Harbor
would make him worse,

25:12.056 --> 25:14.995
but I wanted to go anyway.

25:15.029 --> 25:18.770
[soft dramatic music]

25:18.803 --> 25:22.644
♪ ♪

25:22.677 --> 25:23.646
Dad?

25:23.679 --> 25:27.921
♪ ♪

25:27.954 --> 25:29.658
‐ My Percy.

25:29.691 --> 25:36.237
♪ ♪

25:45.322 --> 25:46.792
Fuck.

25:46.826 --> 25:50.633
♪ ♪

25:50.667 --> 25:53.105
Oh, fuck.

25:55.142 --> 25:56.779
‐ We managed to avoid
each other

25:56.812 --> 25:58.983
until a few days later.

25:59.016 --> 26:00.754
[knocking]

26:00.787 --> 26:02.123
[door opens]

26:05.095 --> 26:07.299
‐ Hey.
‐ Hi.

26:10.072 --> 26:11.241
‐ I've been looking for you.

26:13.713 --> 26:17.319
You, uh, you weren't
in your usual spot.

26:19.858 --> 26:22.129
That beach down by the docks.

26:25.369 --> 26:27.707
I pay attention sometimes.

26:27.741 --> 26:31.080
‐ Does Grams need me?
‐ Ah, no, no, um,

26:31.114 --> 26:33.351
she's just closing up.

26:33.385 --> 26:36.057
And Colin's finishing up
his haul right now.

26:39.130 --> 26:42.069
So, uh...

26:42.103 --> 26:45.075
I was on the office computer,

26:45.109 --> 26:47.079
and I saw
you left your browser up.

26:47.981 --> 26:50.085
You've been looking
at apartments in Portland?

26:50.119 --> 26:52.223
‐ Oh, no.

26:52.256 --> 26:55.864
I mean, um, I just do that
when I'm bored sometimes.

26:55.897 --> 26:57.834
You know, Zillow daydreams.

26:59.738 --> 27:03.378
‐ If you're thinking
of leaving,

27:03.411 --> 27:05.048
maybe you should.

27:08.355 --> 27:12.062
‐ I can't leave.
‐ Why not?

27:13.298 --> 27:15.402
‐ Um, what about Grams?

27:15.435 --> 27:18.275
And‐‐and‐‐

27:18.308 --> 27:23.218
and you and Colin
and the business?

27:23.251 --> 27:28.629
‐ Percy, you gotta start
taking care of yourself.

27:30.834 --> 27:32.169
If you don't...

27:34.106 --> 27:36.311
you'll just end up like me.

27:36.344 --> 27:40.052
[soft dramatic music]

27:40.085 --> 27:47.366
♪ ♪

27:48.301 --> 27:52.109
You have to pay a deposit
on a place in Portland.

27:52.142 --> 27:54.280
It may take a while
to find a job.

27:54.313 --> 27:56.785
‐ Dad, I can't take this.

27:58.154 --> 27:59.892
‐ Let me do this
one thing for you.

28:02.096 --> 28:03.431
Just go.

28:05.469 --> 28:07.106
Don't tell Grams.

28:10.245 --> 28:11.749
Just do it.

28:11.782 --> 28:16.992
♪ ♪

28:17.026 --> 28:18.796
‐ What's gonna happen to you?

28:18.829 --> 28:23.773
♪ ♪

28:23.806 --> 28:27.914
‐ I'll figure it out.
I will.

28:27.948 --> 28:30.954
♪ ♪

28:30.987 --> 28:34.193
‐ Dad, it's‐‐

28:34.227 --> 28:37.466
it's my fault.

28:37.499 --> 28:40.339
That night.

28:40.372 --> 28:43.178
I mean, if you had‐‐
if you hadn't gone there,

28:43.211 --> 28:45.984
you never would've
needed those pills.

28:46.017 --> 28:47.887
♪ ♪

28:47.921 --> 28:52.831
‐ Everything that's happened
is on all of us.

28:52.864 --> 28:56.772
♪ ♪

29:05.455 --> 29:10.065
‐ This felt like
the right symbol for her."Ties that bind,"
all knotted up.

29:10.098 --> 29:13.004
‐ Mothers and daughters.

29:13.038 --> 29:14.908
It's never easy.

29:16.411 --> 29:18.381
‐ You're back where
you're supposed to be.

29:18.415 --> 29:20.385
‐ Because I can't handle
anywhere else.

29:20.419 --> 29:24.226
‐ No, you're just
in a rough patch.

29:24.260 --> 29:27.466
You'll get through.
You're a Muldoon.

29:30.238 --> 29:32.242
You know,
when I lost your grandfather,

29:32.276 --> 29:34.380
I was in a black hole.

29:34.413 --> 29:36.819
I couldn't see
the horizon anywhere.

29:38.522 --> 29:40.292
I had two little kids,

29:40.325 --> 29:42.897
and everybody in town was
talking behind my back,

29:42.931 --> 29:48.809
saying I was gonna fail
because I didn't have Jerry.

29:50.445 --> 29:51.915
You know how I got through?

29:51.949 --> 29:54.353
‐ Yeah, you've told me
this like a million times.

29:55.455 --> 29:58.361
‐ 'Cause it's true.

29:58.395 --> 30:00.265
Work keeps you strong.

30:02.169 --> 30:03.839
It's in our blood.

30:04.908 --> 30:08.381
Yeah.
And we need you back.

30:16.164 --> 30:18.468
‐ What if I don't want it?

30:18.501 --> 30:22.544
‐ Of course you do.
You're a born leader.

30:26.417 --> 30:28.254
‐ Grams, um...

30:29.958 --> 30:32.530
I've thought about it,

30:32.564 --> 30:34.367
and I know
I'm the only one after Colin,

30:34.400 --> 30:36.839
but I don't want it.

30:39.310 --> 30:40.947
‐ I think you're just tired.

30:43.451 --> 30:45.322
‐ I'm serious.

30:45.355 --> 30:47.493
Just thinking about it makes me
feel like I'm drowning.

30:47.527 --> 30:49.063
I don't want any of it.

30:49.096 --> 30:51.234
‐ So what are you gonna do?
Just let it all die?

30:51.267 --> 30:54.373
‐ No, the Keysers
could take it over.

30:54.407 --> 30:55.610
Brandon would want it.

30:55.643 --> 30:59.083
‐ You do realize I'm doing
everything for you?

30:59.116 --> 31:03.158
This house, the plant,
the boats. It's all for you.

31:03.191 --> 31:04.293
‐ But that's what you want.

31:04.326 --> 31:06.464
‐ You have no idea
how lucky you are.

31:08.068 --> 31:12.042
Four generations of Muldoons
have built this business,

31:12.076 --> 31:14.213
this house, this room.

31:14.246 --> 31:18.288
You're living on their backs.
And what are you gonna do?

31:18.321 --> 31:21.962
Throw it all away and go back
to folding clothes at a mall.

31:23.098 --> 31:24.366
[sighs]

31:24.400 --> 31:26.204
I'm not talking
about this anymore.

31:26.237 --> 31:28.141
[soft ominous music]

31:28.174 --> 31:29.978
♪ ♪

31:30.011 --> 31:32.382
‐ Meg was never gonna
let her go.

31:32.416 --> 31:35.122
[fire crackling]

31:35.155 --> 31:39.463
♪ ♪

31:39.497 --> 31:41.568
‐ This is for Colin.

31:41.602 --> 31:44.373
‐ No, this is Colin.

31:44.407 --> 31:51.487
♪ ♪

31:52.690 --> 31:58.034
‐ I tried to apologize.

31:58.067 --> 32:00.305
Like we talked about.

32:00.338 --> 32:06.083
♪ ♪

32:06.117 --> 32:09.490
‐ Hey.
‐ How's it going?

32:09.524 --> 32:11.662
‐ I got shrimp frying.
What's up?

32:12.630 --> 32:14.500
‐ I just wanted to say...

32:16.705 --> 32:18.676
I'm sorry.

32:18.709 --> 32:21.915
I really do appreciate what
you're trying to do for me.

32:23.017 --> 32:24.220
‐ Okay.

32:24.253 --> 32:26.390
‐ Look, I know recommitting
to the Church has helped you.

32:26.424 --> 32:30.666
And I'm happy
you found something.

32:30.700 --> 32:34.674
But it just wasn't
working for me.

32:34.708 --> 32:37.514
‐ Well, to be honest,
uh, you never really tried,

32:37.547 --> 32:39.518
so what do you expect?

32:41.220 --> 32:43.057
‐ I don't know. I‐‐

32:45.328 --> 32:47.466
I guess I don't see the world
the way you do.

32:47.499 --> 32:49.971
‐ Oh, and how's that?

32:51.474 --> 32:53.044
‐ It doesn't matter.

32:53.077 --> 32:54.714
‐ No. No, tell me.

32:56.585 --> 33:01.360
‐ I'm not sure the world
is so black and white,

33:01.394 --> 33:02.496
right and wrong.

33:02.530 --> 33:05.235
‐ So what,
you don't believe in God?

33:05.268 --> 33:07.172
‐ Look, I feel judged enough
as it is, okay?

33:07.206 --> 33:08.542
‐ Oh, we all do.
‐ Yeah.

33:08.576 --> 33:09.744
Well, you don't have
to deal with it like I do.

33:09.778 --> 33:11.480
‐ Do you think
this has been easy on us?

33:11.515 --> 33:13.051
Cleaning up your shit?

33:14.788 --> 33:16.758
Someone died.

33:16.792 --> 33:18.161
Quit feeling sorry
for yourself.

33:18.194 --> 33:19.396
Grow the fuck up.

33:19.430 --> 33:23.037
[downbeat dramatic music]

33:23.071 --> 33:24.206
‐ Someone died?

33:24.240 --> 33:28.616
♪ ♪

33:28.649 --> 33:30.620
Is that who this is?

33:30.653 --> 33:34.093
♪ ♪

33:34.126 --> 33:35.095
None of this will work

33:35.128 --> 33:37.266
if you're not willing
to face what happened.

33:37.299 --> 33:40.773
♪ ♪

33:40.806 --> 33:44.246
Whatever it was.

33:44.280 --> 33:45.783
‐ I can't.

33:45.816 --> 33:49.390
♪ ♪

33:49.423 --> 33:51.695
‐ Take it.

33:51.728 --> 33:53.264
We haven't been working
for months

33:53.298 --> 33:55.235
for you to give into fear.

33:55.268 --> 33:58.174
[dramatic music]

33:58.208 --> 34:05.121
♪ ♪

34:29.370 --> 34:30.773
‐ Percy!

34:31.775 --> 34:35.048
Percy, stop!
You're hurting yourself!

34:36.150 --> 34:37.119
‐ I can't do this!

34:37.152 --> 34:40.258
♪ ♪

34:40.292 --> 34:41.595
‐ Wait.

34:41.628 --> 34:44.466
Wait, don't go like this.

34:44.500 --> 34:46.571
Please, please!

34:51.882 --> 34:55.121
I never should have pushed her
the way I did.

34:57.560 --> 34:59.163
It was my fault.

35:01.902 --> 35:05.776
♪ ♪

35:05.810 --> 35:07.647
‐ Percy said that
she was responsible

35:07.680 --> 35:10.385
for somebody's death.

35:10.418 --> 35:12.322
‐ She never told me who.

35:12.356 --> 35:17.199
♪ ♪

35:17.232 --> 35:22.644
‐ Do you know if that
person's name was Valerie?

35:22.677 --> 35:25.750
‐ I've never seen that before.

35:25.783 --> 35:28.689
She must have written this
after our ritual.

35:28.722 --> 35:36.170
♪ ♪

35:36.738 --> 35:39.310
Do you think you can
push someone to suicide?

35:39.343 --> 35:43.552
♪ ♪

35:43.585 --> 35:48.261
‐ I know you can't save someone
who doesn't want to be saved.

35:48.294 --> 35:53.639
♪ ♪

35:53.672 --> 35:55.241
‐ Then why are you still here?

36:11.942 --> 36:13.812
So we're the same, you and I.

36:16.752 --> 36:18.388
We're both guilty.

36:20.693 --> 36:22.329
‐ I don't know.

36:23.966 --> 36:25.335
Maybe.

36:28.575 --> 36:30.478
‐ I wish you could
let Jamie go.

36:30.513 --> 36:32.850
‐ Don't.
‐ And Sonya.

36:32.884 --> 36:34.854
‐ Don't start.
‐ And Faye.

36:34.888 --> 36:36.290
‐ Over and over
and over she died.

36:36.323 --> 36:38.729
‐ Your mother.
‐ No, you stop.

36:38.762 --> 36:40.800
‐ I can't.

36:40.833 --> 36:42.503
I'm living in your mind.

36:42.537 --> 36:44.473
[ominous music]

36:44.507 --> 36:46.410
♪ ♪

36:46.444 --> 36:49.651
It's like a spiral going down.

36:51.320 --> 36:52.122
If you don't stop,

36:52.155 --> 36:54.861
you're gonna end up doing
what I did.

36:54.894 --> 36:56.798
‐ Maybe that's what I deserve.

36:56.832 --> 37:01.675
♪ ♪

37:01.708 --> 37:04.246
‐ No one deserves that.

37:04.279 --> 37:08.321
♪ ♪

37:08.354 --> 37:11.595
‐ I killed a man
when I didn't have to.

37:11.628 --> 37:18.675
♪ ♪

37:54.848 --> 37:57.987
[line trilling] [phone buzzing]

38:06.638 --> 38:08.809
‐ Hello?

38:08.842 --> 38:12.750
‐ Hi.
Where are you?

38:12.783 --> 38:14.486
‐ Running an errand.

38:14.521 --> 38:16.892
‐ Oh, yeah?
Where are you going?

38:18.529 --> 38:20.833
‐ Where are you?

38:20.866 --> 38:22.503
‐ I'm still here.

38:29.751 --> 38:31.420
I finally slept last night.

38:33.659 --> 38:34.894
‐ That's good.

38:36.898 --> 38:38.100
Oh.

38:38.134 --> 38:41.073
So I, uh‐‐I actually
was gonna call you.

38:41.106 --> 38:45.481
It turns out, they did take
something, whoever broke in.

38:45.516 --> 38:49.757
A stack of photographs that I
had printed and a thumb drive.

38:49.791 --> 38:52.530
‐ What would they want
with your pictures?

38:52.563 --> 38:56.470
‐ I don't know, Harry.
I backed them up on the cloud.

38:56.505 --> 39:00.478
I can send them to you
so you can, I dunno,

39:00.513 --> 39:04.521
check for whatever it is
that you're looking for.

39:07.025 --> 39:09.062
‐ Yeah.
If you wouldn't mind.

39:09.931 --> 39:11.400
‐ Yep.

39:15.676 --> 39:19.416
Well, I'll go now if that's‐‐
if that's all.

39:23.559 --> 39:25.128
‐ Okay.

39:25.161 --> 39:27.132
[line beeps]

39:27.165 --> 39:30.104
[dramatic music]

39:30.138 --> 39:32.375
♪ ♪

39:32.409 --> 39:33.545
[phone chimes]

39:33.579 --> 39:40.526
♪ ♪

40:04.172 --> 40:05.709
[knock at door]

40:09.082 --> 40:11.186
Good morning.

40:11.220 --> 40:13.959
‐ You know why I'm here.

40:13.992 --> 40:16.030
I thought we had
an arrangement.

40:18.835 --> 40:20.138
You've been lying to me.

40:21.708 --> 40:22.743
‐ No.

40:22.777 --> 40:25.516
‐ Then what were you doing
with that witch woman?

40:27.185 --> 40:28.922
‐ What do you mean?

40:28.956 --> 40:30.491
‐ I knew something was up

40:30.526 --> 40:32.596
when you left
the harbor master's office.

40:33.732 --> 40:35.803
What did she do
to my granddaughter?

40:35.836 --> 40:38.107
‐ She didn't hurt Percy.

40:38.140 --> 40:40.111
Percy came to her for help.

40:40.144 --> 40:42.750
‐ And you believe her?

40:42.783 --> 40:45.021
She wouldn't even say
that much to me.

40:46.858 --> 40:48.996
‐ You talked to her.

40:49.029 --> 40:50.498
‐ Well, I'm not gonna
sit around

40:50.532 --> 40:52.536
and wait for you to decide
what to tell me.

40:55.041 --> 40:58.682
‐ I needed to talk to her.
Just one‐on‐one.

40:58.715 --> 41:01.053
‐ And what did you learn
one‐on‐one?

41:03.692 --> 41:05.996
‐ Do you know anything
about this guilt

41:06.030 --> 41:07.198
that Percy was carrying around?

41:07.232 --> 41:10.471
‐ Most women are raised to
feel guilty about everything,

41:10.506 --> 41:11.675
but I taught Percy different.

41:14.212 --> 41:16.785
‐ But for some reason,

41:16.818 --> 41:19.524
she felt responsible
for somebody's death.

41:21.828 --> 41:23.799
‐ Whose?

41:23.832 --> 41:28.709
‐ Is there anyone in her life
that‐‐maybe recently who died?

41:28.742 --> 41:29.811
‐ No.

41:29.844 --> 41:32.048
And that nut job is leading you
down the wrong road.

41:32.082 --> 41:33.250
I'm taking this to Lou.

41:33.284 --> 41:37.560
‐ Meg, just‐‐hold on.

41:38.294 --> 41:41.100
Sonya took some photographs
while she was here.

41:42.770 --> 41:44.807
This is one of them.
‐ [unzips fanny pack]

41:45.876 --> 41:48.849
‐ Two boats pulled together
that way.

41:48.882 --> 41:50.753
Anything strange about it?

41:50.786 --> 41:52.055
‐ I don't know about
the other one,

41:52.088 --> 41:54.059
but that's a Keyser boat.

41:54.092 --> 41:56.631
[ominous music]

41:56.664 --> 42:01.808
‐ Whose?
‐ Brandon's. Why?

42:01.841 --> 42:06.818
‐ During the break‐in, the only
thing taken were these photos.

42:06.851 --> 42:08.889
♪ ♪

42:08.922 --> 42:13.064
‐ Brandon brings his haul
in around lunchtime.

42:13.097 --> 42:16.036
His boat's coming in
right about now.

42:16.070 --> 42:20.713
♪ ♪

42:38.086 --> 42:39.987
‐ I don't know what to think
about any of this anymore.

42:39.987 --> 42:41.888
It's like the vertigo I felt
after my stroke.

42:41.921 --> 42:43.190
No solid ground.

42:45.128 --> 42:46.063
‐ Yeah, I'll bet.

42:46.096 --> 42:49.302
[boat horns blowing]

42:59.389 --> 43:02.630
‐ I don't blame you
for not trusting me.

43:05.368 --> 43:09.109
I haven't been completely
honest with you

43:09.142 --> 43:13.785
about Sean,
Percy's time off‐island.

43:15.154 --> 43:18.060
But you have to understand that
this is a very small town.

43:18.093 --> 43:19.664
People talk.

43:21.166 --> 43:24.941
They smile at you, but they
don't wish you the best.

43:27.646 --> 43:29.750
It's made me a private person.

43:32.723 --> 43:34.594
‐ I know how that can happen.

43:45.281 --> 43:46.951
‐ There's the Keyser clunker.

43:49.857 --> 43:51.160
What the hell?

43:51.193 --> 43:54.266
He's not turning.
Brandon?

43:54.299 --> 43:56.270
Hey!

43:56.303 --> 43:59.376
There's no one
behind the wheel!

43:59.409 --> 44:02.382
[tense music]

44:02.415 --> 44:09.162
♪ ♪

44:10.097 --> 44:15.174
Set to autopilot to
return itself back to the dock.

44:15.208 --> 44:18.180
‐ What is it?
How does it work? Is it real?

44:18.214 --> 44:19.750
‐ What is that?

44:19.784 --> 44:22.857
‐ No idea what the hell
cryptocurrency is.

44:22.890 --> 44:24.760
Now, there are countless
cryptocurrencies

44:24.794 --> 44:28.167
in the universe, with new ones
popping up almost daily.

44:28.200 --> 44:29.770
I don't know which way is up.

44:29.804 --> 44:31.741
When producer Dan suggested
this topic, I tried‐‐

44:31.774 --> 44:34.179
‐ It's just a speaker.

44:34.212 --> 44:37.418
♪ ♪

44:37.452 --> 44:39.155
‐ What am I supposed
to be looking for?

44:39.189 --> 44:41.694
‐ Well, you know what usually
a boat has.

44:41.728 --> 44:43.063
What looks strange?

44:43.097 --> 44:45.101
Anything outta place
or something shouldn't be here,

44:45.134 --> 44:46.136
I guess.

